\'93I shall be delighted to meet them,\'94 said the prince. \'93But tell me,\'94 he added with studied carelessness as if it had only just occurred to him, though the question he was about to ask was the chief motive of his visit, \'93is it true that the Dowager Empress wants Baron Funke to be appointed first secretary at Vienna? The baron by all accounts is a poor creature.\'94\
Prince Vas\'edli wished to obtain this post for his son, but others were trying through the Dowager Empress M\'e1rya F\'ebdorovna to secure it for the baron.\
Anna P\'e1vlovna almost closed her eyes to indicate that neither she nor anyone else had a right to criticize what the Empress desired or was pleased with.\
\'93Baron Funke has been recommended to the Dowager Empress by her sister,\'94 was all she said, in a dry and mournful tone.\
As she named the Empress, Anna P\'e1vlovna\'92s face suddenly assumed an expression of profound and sincere devotion and respect mingled with sadness, and this occurred every time she mentioned her illustrious patroness. She added that Her Majesty had deigned to show Baron Funke\'a0
\f1\i beaucoup d\'92estime
\f0\i0 , and again her face clouded over with sadness.\
The prince was silent and looked indifferent. But, with the womanly and courtierlike quickness and tact habitual to her, Anna P\'e1vlovna wished both to rebuke him (for daring to speak as he had done of a man recommended to the Empress) and at the same time to console him, so she said:\
\'93Now about your family. Do you know that since your daughter came out everyone has been enraptured by her? They say she is amazingly beautiful.\'94\
The prince bowed to signify his respect and gratitude.\
\'93I often think,\'94 she continued after a short pause, drawing nearer to the prince and smiling amiably at him as if to show that political and social topics were ended and the time had come for intimate conversation\'97\'93I often think how unfairly sometimes the joys of life are distributed. Why has fate given you two such splendid children? I don\'92t speak of Anatole, your youngest. I don\'92t like him,\'94 she added in a tone admitting of no rejoinder and raising her eyebrows. \'93Two such charming children. And really you appreciate them less than anyone, and so you don\'92t deserve to have them.\'94\
And she smiled her ecstatic smile.\
\'93I can\'92t help it,\'94 said the prince. \'93Lavater would have said I lack the bump of paternity.\'94\
\'93Don\'92t joke; I mean to have a serious talk with you. Do you know I am dissatisfied with your younger son? Between ourselves\'94 (and her face assumed its melancholy expression), \'93he was mentioned at Her Majesty\'92s and you were pitied....\'94\
The prince answered nothing, but she looked at him significantly, awaiting a reply. He frowned.\
\'93What would you have me do?\'94 he said at last. \'93You know I did all a father could for their education, and they have both turned out fools. Hippolyte is at least a quiet fool, but Anatole is an active one. That is the only difference between them.\'94 He said this smiling in a way more natural and animated than usual, so that the wrinkles round his mouth very clearly revealed something unexpectedly coarse and unpleasant.\
\'93And why are children born to such men as you? If you were not a father there would be nothing I could reproach you with,\'94 said Anna P\'e1vlovna, looking up pensively.\
\'93I am your faithful slave and to you alone I can confess that my children are the bane of my life. It is the cross I have to bear. That is how I explain it to myself. It can\'92t be helped!\'94\
He said no more, but expressed his resignation to cruel fate by a gesture. Anna P\'e1vlovna meditated.\
\'93Have you never thought of marrying your prodigal son Anatole?\'94 she asked. \'93They say old maids have a mania for matchmaking, and though I don\'92t feel that weakness in myself as yet, I know a little person who is very unhappy with her father. She is a relation of yours, Princess Mary Bolk\'f3nskaya.\'94\
Prince Vas\'edli did not reply, though, with the quickness of memory and perception befitting a man of the world, he indicated by a movement of the head that he was considering this information.\
\'93Do you know,\'94 he said at last, evidently unable to check the sad current of his thoughts, \'93that Anatole is costing me forty thousand rubles a year? And,\'94 he went on after a pause, \'93what will it be in five years, if he goes on like this?\'94 Presently he added: \'93That\'92s what we fathers have to put up with.... Is this princess of yours rich?\'94\
\'93Her father is very rich and stingy. He lives in the country. He is the well-known Prince Bolk\'f3nski who had to retire from the army under the late Emperor, and was nicknamed \'91the King of Prussia.\'92 He is very clever but eccentric, and a bore. The poor girl is very unhappy. She has a brother; I think you know him, he married Lise Meinen lately. He is an aide-de-camp of Kut\'fazov\'92s and will be here tonight.\'94\
\'93Listen, dear Annette,\'94 said the prince, suddenly taking Anna P\'e1vlovna\'92s hand and for some reason drawing it downwards. \'93Arrange that affair for me and I shall always be your most devoted slave-
